title: For Sale:  Extremely Rare German Sniper Rifle 1 of 6 known Stateside.
postcontent: For sale I have an all original German made sniper rifle that was brought home as a war trophy from WW2. From the extensive research I've done since owning this masterpiece I've been able to ascertain its a Danzig Model 1898 Sporting Rifle and here is the history I've been able to find out behind the rifle: These guns were produced In 1919 only by the Danzig factory In Germany after the treaty of versallies left the Danzig factory without a military contract so they were forced to produce firearms for the civilian market to try and stay financially viable. These rifles were overly expensive and not easily attained by the common person therefore only an estimated 1500-1800 of these rifles were ever produced. Adding to the rariety is the fact they were never imported into the US so the only ones stateside were the ones brought back as war trophies. This gun exhibits old world craftsmanship with deluxe wood, fine checkering, a scnabel forend, raised cheek piece, raised forend, and double set triggers. A rifle like this today would cost in excess of $5000 with the amount of work and fine craftmanship put into it. According to my research this is the lowest known serial number stateside at serial number 626. This rifle is in near perfect condition retaining 90-95% of its high polish blue finish and partial case color on bolt and receiver area. Bore is perfect with no pitting. This is all topped off by and original DR. Gerard 3 post 4 power scope with quick detach high turret mount that is in great condition as well. I've shot this firearm and it still exhibits excellant accuracy almost 100 years after being manufactured. Here is your chance to own an extremely rare early sniping rifle. The only other examples I have seen sell sold at auction for $2800 and $3000 respectively so price is firm. Will consider RESONABLE cash offers. title: For Sale:  CZECH Republic VZ.58 MILITARY 7.62X39 D-TECHNIK
postcontent:
vz.58 Military
Imported from Czechoslovakia and manufactured D-Technik, NOT CENTURY ARMS
- Built on milled receiver
- 7.62x39 caliber and take all standard ammo corrosive and non-corrosive)
- Czech made cold hammer forged chrome lined barrels. 

1600 OR BEST OFFER 


Advantages of Sa vz. 58 over AK47 rifles (cited from Richard Rich Chris)
- All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK47s utilize stamped sheet metal receivers and are not as rigid as the vz.58 receiver.
- Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK47.
- The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired – the shooter immediately knows the firearm is empty and allows for quicker reloads.
- The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle.
- The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling.
- The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58. Unlike the AK safety, the vz. 58 safety can be operated by just a forefinger with the hand remaining on the pistol grip.
- vz.58 has no need for an ejection port dust cover as the receiver is completely enclosed. A cover (on the safety lever) must be used on the AK47 to prevent debris from entering the receiver through the reciprocating charging handle slot.
- The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the vz. 58.
- The vz. 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
- The alloy magazine of the vz. 58 is half the weight of the steel AK47 magazine.
- The vz. 58 is striker fired unlike the hammer fired AK47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.

title: For Sale:  VZ.58 Military 7.62x39 D-Technik not Century Arms
postcontent:
vz.58 Military
Imported from Czechoslovakia and manufactured D-Technik, NOT CENTURY ARMS
- Built on milled receiver
- 7.62x39 caliber and take all standard ammo corrosive and non-corrosive)
- Czech made cold hammer forged chrome lined barrels. 

1600 OR BEST OFFER 


Advantages of Sa vz. 58 over AK47 rifles (cited from Richard Rich Chris)
- All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK47s utilize stamped sheet metal receivers and are not as rigid as the vz.58 receiver.
- Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK47.
- The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired – the shooter immediately knows the firearm is empty and allows for quicker reloads.
- The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle.
- The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling.
- The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58. Unlike the AK safety, the vz. 58 safety can be operated by just a forefinger with the hand remaining on the pistol grip.
- vz.58 has no need for an ejection port dust cover as the receiver is completely enclosed. A cover (on the safety lever) must be used on the AK47 to prevent debris from entering the receiver through the reciprocating charging handle slot.
- The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the vz. 58.
- The vz. 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
- The alloy magazine of the vz. 58 is half the weight of the steel AK47 magazine.
- The vz. 58 is striker fired unlike the hammer fired AK47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.

title: For Sale:  RARE! SLEEVE! Smith & Wesson Model 27-2 357 Magnum         27 6" Box Papers Grip Fit 29 57 629 66 Vintage P&R
postcontent:
he Smith & Wesson Model 27 is the original .357 Magnum revolver and was first produced in 1935, and many versions of it are still in production today. The Model 27 was built on Smith & Wesson's carbon steel, large N-frame, and was available at various times with 31/2", 4", 5", 6" or 83/8" barrel lengths and had adjustable sights.
History

When first introduced by Smith & Wesson in 1935 it was known as the Registered Magnum. The model was essentially a custom order revolver. Barrel lengths could be had in quarter-inch increments from 3.5" to 8.75" in length. In addition to the different lengths of barrels available there were different grips, front sights, triggers, hammers, and finishes available. Each Registered Magnum came with a certificate of authenticity. Even though it was introduced in the middle of the Great Depression and was extremely expensive, Smith & Wesson found itself backlogged with orders for the four years that it produced the Registered Magnum. The Kansas City Police Department issued the Registered Magnum to its officers, and many other law enforcement officers across the United States carried the Registered Magnum. In 1939 Smith & Wesson stopped producing the Registered Magnum. It was replaced with the .357 Magnum. The .357 Magnum was available with barrel lengths of 3.5", 5", 6.5" and 8.75". It has been reported that these were the most popular barrel lengths for the Registered Magnum. Essentially the .357 Magnum was still the Registered Magnum, but standardized for ease of production and economy. The Smith & Wesson Model 28 "Highway Patrolman" was introduced as a lower cost version of the Model 27 in 1954, stripped of some of the features of the Model 27, such as polishing.

It was noted for its durability and reliability. The 31/2" barrel length was extremely popular with FBI agents from the 1940s through the 1960s. Skeeter Skelton considered the Model 27 with a 5" barrel as the best all around handgun. General George Patton carried an ivory handled Registered Magnum with a 31/2 inch barrel (along with his ivory handled Colt Peacemaker); Patton called the Model 27 his "killing gun."
